Reusable Web-Based Learning Game Engine
Core Systems Competition — Checkpoint 1
Team Information
Team Name: Noir12

1. Introduction
Educational games are commonly developed as standalone applications where the game logic and
educational content are tightly coupled. This approach limits scalability, reusability, and rapid
content creation.
Our project proposes a Reusable Web-Based Learning Game Engine that separates engine logic,
game modules, and learning content. The engine allows multiple educational games to be
generated dynamically using JSON configuration files, eliminating the need to modify core engine
code when creating new learning experiences.
This design enables educators and developers to create new games by simply modifying
configuration files while the engine handles execution, rendering, and gameplay logic.

2. System Objectives
The primary objectives of the system are:
• Develop a modular and reusable game engine
• Support multiple learning game types
• Enable JSON-driven configuration
• Maintain separation between logic and content
• Ensure scalability and extensibility
The system is designed so that new game types and educational content can be added without
modifying the engine core.

3. System Architecture
The architecture of the engine follows a modular layered design.The system is composed of the following components:
JSON Configuration Layer
Contains all game definitions including rules, content, UI settings, and difficulty parameters.
Config Loader
Responsible for loading and validating JSON configuration files before the game begins.
Game Engine Core
The central controller responsible for managing game state, initializing modules, and running the
engine loop.
Module System
Game mechanics are implemented as modules such as quiz, memory, or drag-and-drop games.
UI Renderer
Responsible for rendering the game interface and displaying interactive elements.
Input Handler
Captures user actions and sends events to the engine.

System Diagram
JSON Configuration
↓
Config Loader
↓
Game Engine Core
↓
Module Registry
↓
Game Modules
(Quiz / Memory / Drag-Drop)
↓
UI Renderer
↓
Player InteractionArchitecture Flow

The system operates according to the following flow:
1. Game configuration is loaded from a JSON file.
2. The configuration is parsed and validated by the Config Loader.
3. The Game Engine initializes the appropriate module based on the gameType.
4. The engine starts the game loop.
5. User input is processed and the game state is updated.
6. The UI Renderer updates the game interface.
7. The process repeats until the game ends.
4. Core Engine Loop

The engine operates using a continuous control loop that manages gameplay.
Engine Loop Steps
1. Load configuration
2. Initialize game module
3. Process user input
4. Update game state
5. Render updated UI
6. Check win/termination conditions
7. Repeat until game completion

Engine Loop Pseudocode

loadConfig()
initializeModule()
while(gameRunning):
input = getUserInput()
updateGameState(input)
renderUI()
checkGameEndCondition()
This loop allows the same engine to support multiple game types while maintaining consistent
execution flow.5. JSON Configuration Design
The engine is designed to be JSON-driven, meaning that game behavior and content are defined
entirely through configuration files.
Each configuration file contains information about:
• game type
• metadata
• gameplay settings
• educational content
• UI preferences
JSON Schema Structure
{
}
"engineVersion": "1.0",
"gameType": "quiz",
"metadata": {
"title": "Math Challenge",
"author": "Team"
},
"settings": {
"timeLimit": 30,
"maxScore": 100,
"difficulty": "easy"
},
"content": {
"questions": [
{
"id": 1,
"question": "2 + 3 = ?",
"options": ["4", "5", "6"],
"answer": "5"
}
]
},
"ui": {
"theme": "light",
"showTimer": true
}

6. Reusability Model
The system follows a component-based modular architecture to maximize reusability.
Game mechanics are implemented as independent modules that follow a standardized interface.Example Modules
• Quiz Module
• Memory Matching Module
• Drag-and-Drop Module
• Sequence Builder Module
Each module implements the following functions:
init(config)
update(input)
render()
endGame()
Because of this design:
• The engine core remains unchanged
• Modules define gameplay behavior
• JSON defines learning content
This enables rapid creation of new games without modifying the engine logic.

7. Module Registry System
To support extensibility, the engine uses a module registry system.
Modules register themselves with the engine and are dynamically loaded based on the gameType
specified in the JSON configuration.
Example:
registerModule("quiz", QuizModule)
registerModule("memory", MemoryModule)
When a configuration file specifies:
"gameType": "quiz"
the engine automatically loads the corresponding module.
This allows the engine to support new game types without modifying existing code.

8. Example Learning Games Generated by the
Engine
Using the same engine, multiple educational games can be created:
• Mathematics Quiz
• Vocabulary Builder
• Capital Cities Quiz• Memory Matching Game
• Image Identification Game
Each of these games is generated using different JSON configurations while the engine code
remains unchanged.

9. Scalability and Extensibility
The architecture is designed to support future enhancements including:
• additional game modules
• multiplayer learning modes
• analytics and progress tracking
• teacher dashboards
• adaptive difficulty systems
The modular design ensures that these features can be integrated without restructuring the core
engine.

10. Conclusion
This project demonstrates the design of a reusable learning game engine that separates gameplay
logic from educational content using JSON configuration.
The modular architecture allows the engine to generate multiple learning experiences while
maintaining scalability and extensibility.
By focusing on clean system architecture, modular design, and configuration-driven gameplay,
the engine provides a flexible platform for building interactive educational games.
